<b>Proposed Design</b>

<b>The Los Angeles METRO</b>

{image 44}<figcaption>Metro Rail and Busway Overview Map, metro.net <a href="https://www.metro.net/riding/guide/system-maps/" target="_blank">link</a></figcaption>
<b>Public transit + Amenities Concept</b>

{image 42}<figcaption>Metro Red Line + Amenities system proposal, Eric Lin & Saly Chae (2018).</figcaption>

<b>Site</b>
The <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Vermont+%2F+Sunset+Station/@34.0910611,-118.293523,974a,35y,39.16t/data=!3m1!1e3!4m8!1m2!2m1!1ssunset+and+vermont+metro!3m4!1s0x0:0x93d640f7621ae557!8m2!3d34.0983692!4d-118.2914519" target="_blank"">Sunset/Vermont Metro</a> stop is an epicenter to a multitude of Healthcare Facilities; at the heart of Los Angeles. The vicinity poses a unique opportunity for implementing MetroNaka's design strategy toward a healthcare-oriented setting.

{image 40}
<figcaption>"MetroNaka + Sunset/Vermont Site Plan" Sally Chae 2019.</figcaption>

<b>Diagrams</b>
The central design motion of the project is a descending ramp that steps and levels downward along the lengths of the site. The rectangular steps are then carved into a single, gently sloping ramp downward.

{image 34}
<figcaption>"Descending, Carving and Circulating" Sally Chae 2019.</figcaption>

The space beneath the ramp is carved out; to create a programmable innard beneath each ramp and corresponding platform's surface. In essence, this project is a descending ramp that one may also enter as a carved-out cave @ floor-by-floor increments.
{image 35}
<figcaption>"Step-by-step, Geometricity and Carved Innards" Sally Chae 2019.</figcaption>

<b>Exploded Isometric</b>
The floor-to-floor view shows from groundlevel, to B1, B2, down to B3; of all the programmable possibilities the descending and carved ramp may contain on its exterior and interior.
{image 1}
<figcaption>"Circulation/Spatial/Program - Iso Diagram" Sally Chae 2019.</figcaption>

<b>Plan</b>
Floor plans demonstrate a rigor toward geometricity while aiming toward a user-friendly, sloping environment. The challenge of the plan involved successfully joining maximizing the site's square footage for programmable space while creating geometric opportunities other than a strictly economic/gridded space.
{slideshow}{image 30}{image 29}{image 26}{image 27}{image 28}
{/slideshow}
<figcaption>"MetroNaka + Sunset/Vermont Floor Plans" Sally Chae 2019.</figcaption>

<b>Section</b>
The descent is a green well of alternative programs; a slight departure from the hospital-campuses at groundfloor, and a moment of descent into a retreat-like open-air public space.
{image 37}
<figcaption>"MetroNaka Section" Sally Chae 2019</figcaption>

<b>Physical Model</b>
The model is a quick rendition of how, sectionally, the building's many layers and modes of circulation/program join together in the single path to a Subterranean Metro Terminal/Space.
{slideshow}{image 31}{image 32}{/slideshow}
<figcaption>"MetroNaka + Sunset/Vermont Physical Model" Sally Chae 2019.</figcaption>

